  %p Едене “one” is a true pronominal adjective, and declines regularly according to the inanimate adjective declension paradigm (although the central /e/ disappears in all forms other than the #{abbrev 'nom'}/#{abbrev 'acc'} masculine singular): #{t "една", "iédna"}, #{t "едно", "iédno"}, etc. Like most other pronominal adjectives, it lacks definite forms. The only quirky form is its genitive plural (and therefore animate accusative as well), which is #{t "едних", "iedníh"}, not #{t "**едон", "*iedón"}.
  %p Дова “two” has two forms in the nominative/accusative: #{t "дова", "dóva"} with masculine and neuter nouns, and #{t "довѣ", "dóvě"} with feminine. There are only two other forms for other cases: #{t "довух", "dóvuh"} (#{abbrev 'gen'}/#{abbrev 'loc'}) and #{t "довѣма", "dóvěma"} (#{abbrev 'datins'}). In other cases, the #{abbrev 'nom'}/#{abbrev 'acc'} form is used, including gender agreement. Три/трѣ “three” declines similarly, only having gender agreement in the #{abbrev 'nom'}/#{abbrev 'acc'}.
  %p Цетири “four” and higher decline similarly (see above), but without any gender agreement. Novegradian numeral declension, as can be seen above, has undergone a significant amount of analogical levelling; only two patterns remain, that used by “two” and that used by all other numerals.
  %p The teens are created by taking the digit and adding #{t "-нацити", "-náciti"} (a contracted form of Old Novegradian на дешѧте “upon ten”; the <i>-i</i> is by analogy with дешити and the other numbers 5-9). The incorporated digit may undergo substantial reductions:
