= section "Fractions" do
  %p Novegradian already has its own words for the numbers 0.5, 1.5, and 2.5, which are #{t "пољ", "pół"}, #{t "пољтруга", "połtrugá"}, and #{t "пољтрекьа", "połtrekjá"}, respectively. All other halves are formed as пољ + the genitive form of the number above: #{t "пољ девитех", "pół déviteh"} “8.5”, literally “half of nine”.
  %p Other fractions are made using an ordinal followed by the feminine noun #{t "цести", "césti"} “portion”: #{t "трита цести", "tríta césti"} “one-third”, literally “the third portion”. A cardinal number before it changes the value: #{t "довѣ тритѣ цести", "dóvě trítě cestí"} “two-thirds”, literally “two third portions” (the word “portion” must be put in the genitive case as per the rules of number agreement described later).
  %p The noun цести may be omitted in exchange for making the ordinal definite. However, the case and gender must be the same: #{t "довѣ тритѣе", "dóvě trítěie"}.
  %p Novegradian does have distinct words for “third” and “quarter”, #{t "трете", "tréte"} and #{t "цетуерте", "cetuérte"} respectively, but these are only used in practical physical contexts such as dividing a piece of land or foods like cakes. They never appear in more abstract mathematical contexts (e.g., the number 1/4 is always called #{t "цедиртая", "cedírtaia"}, never #{t "цетуерте", "cetuérte"}) or when the object being quantified is not something that is physically divided and partitioned (e.g., #{t "цедиртая зе луд", "cedírtaia ze lúd"} “a fourth of the people”, never *цетуерте зе луд).
  %p When reading decimals, digits to the right of the decimal are read individually, not as a whole. The decimal mark itself (“,”) is called #{t "зарѣзе", "zárěze"}. Thus, 0,75 is read as #{t "ноље зарѣзе шеньи пети", "nółe zárěze śénji péti"}.

= section "The Singulative One" do
  %p In addition to the regular numeral #{t "едене", "iédene"} for “one”, Novegradian also has the so-called “singulative one” #{t "пољ", "pół"}, identical in form but not in function with the word for “half”. It is used to emphasize that a given noun is one out of what is normally expected to be a group of more than one. Some nouns, such as “leg”, almost always take пољ instead of едене, since legs usually come in two or four: #{t "пољ ногѣ", "pół nogě́"} “one leg”. For nouns that do not necessarily come in groups, there is a semantic difference between the use of едене and пољ. For example, #{t "едене вѣне", "iédene vě́ne"} means “one ship” being discussed on its own, while #{t "пољ вѣна", "pół vě́na"} may better be translated as “one of the ships”, with the implication that this ship is part of a fleet.
  %p Not all instances of “one of the X” in English may be translated into Novegradian using пољ. This can only be done if there is some inherent connection between the one item and the rest of the group, such as the leg or ship in a fleet above. It cannot be used in a sentence such as “This is one of the cities I have visited”; this requires едене as the connection between “this [city]” and “cities I have visited” is too weak and entirely dependent on a single person, rather than being anything inherent.
  %p “One boot” may be distinguished from “half of a boot” by the case of the noun after пољ: genitive for “one”, partitive for “half”: #{t "пољ сабога", "pół sabóga"} “one boot”, #{t "пољ сабогек", "pół sabógek"} “half of a boot”<sup>1</sup>.

= section "Indefinite Numerals" do
  %p Modern Novegradian has three standard indefinite numerals. #{t "Сотоки", "sótoki"} (first declension plural) means “hundreds (of)”, and is used much as in English, utilizing the nominalized form of the numeral #{t "сто", "stó"} “one hundred”. The noun #{t "тема", "temá"} (first declension singular; literally “darkness”) refers to an uncountable multitude, generally used like English “thousands of” or “tens of thousands of”. The phrase #{t "тема-тем", "temá-tem"} (first declension singular; as it literally means “darkness of darknesses”, only the first part declines) is stylistically marked and poetically refers to a seemingly infinite number of something. All of these require the following noun to be in the partitive plural: #{t "тема-тем гуѣздоу", "temá-tem guězdóu"} “a multitude (infinite number of) stars”.
  %p There is no close equivalent to English “tens of” or “dozens of”. Any of a number of non-numerical nouns may be used: #{t "грамада", "gramáda"} “crowd”, #{t "множестуо", "mnóźestuo"} “multitude”, #{t "ред", "réd"} “row”, etc.

= section "Use of Symbols" do
  %p In Novegradian, the comma marks decimals and the full stop separates numerals. “Ten thousand point five” is therefore rendered 10.000,5.
  %p Novegradian has an unusual system for positioning unit symbols. This includes percents (%), currency symbols ($, €, руб, мк, etc), and symbols for weights and measures (л, км, г, etc). In speech, the units may be placed either before or after the number, with slightly different meanings (described in a later section). In writing, the placement of these symbols mirrors their position in speech, so that all may be placed either before or after the number. This leads to unusual sights (by non-Novegradian standards) such as %90, 9.95$, or км400.

= section "Cyrillic Numerals" do
  %p Much like Roman numerals in the West, Novegradian still uses the old Cyrillic numeral system (referred to as #{t "старей стиле", "stárei stíle"} “old style”) in certain situations. It is common to see them on clocks, for writing dates, on lists, marking days of the week (where 1 is Monday and 7 is Sunday), occasionally as page numbers, and often on tombstones.
  %p Derived from the Greek numeral system, the old Cyrillic system includes a number of letters no longer used in Novegradian, much less any Slavic language. For numeration, though, they continue to be used. Every unit from 1-9, ten from 10-90, and hundred from 100-900 are assigned a letter. These are then ordered, largest first, and their values added up. The letter assignments are:
